uld be otherwise. That is the essence of the specifically human.', 1499, 0), (412390, 'He who would be happy should stay at home.', 32355, 0), (412391, 'He who leaves his house in search of happiness pursues a shadow.', 33, 0), (412392, 'It is not irritating to be where one is. It is only irritating to think one would like to be somewhere else.', 1931, 0), (412393, 'Pioneers may be picturesque figures  but they are often rather lonely ones.', 22265, 0), (412394, 'He that is discontented in one place will seldom be happy in another.', 1733, 0), (412395, 'We are under the spell always of what is distant from us. It is not in our nature to desire passionately what is near at hand.', 64994, 0), (412396, 'In all climates  under all skies  man''s happiness is always somewhere else.', 7895, 0), (412397, 'In Rome you long for the country. In the country you praise to the skies the distant town.', 2542, 0), (412398, 'He who would be happy should stay at home.', 32355, 0), (412399, 'Life is a hospital in which every patient is possessed by the desire of changing his bed. One would prefer to suffer near the fire  and another is certain he would get well if he were by the window.', 1165, 0), (412400, 'It is common to overlook what is near by keeping the eye fixed on something remote.', 2087, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (412401, 'There are three wants which can never be satisfied: that of the rich  who want something more  that of the sick  who want something different  and that of the traveler  who says  "Anywhere but here."', 760, 0), (412402, 'Happiness grows at our firesides  and is not to be picked in strangers'' gardens.', 62449, 0), (412403, 'Men run away to other countries because they are not good in their own  and run back to their own because they pass for nothing in the new places.', 760, 0), (412404, 'The proper means of increasing the love we bear our native country is to reside some time in a foreign one.', 63810, 0), (412405, 'If solid happiness we prize  within our breast this jewel lies  And they are fools who roam  the world has nothing to bestow  From our own selves our bliss must flow  And that dear hut-our home.', 62303, 0), (412406, 'A child on a farm sees a plane fly overhead and dreams of a faraway place. A traveler on the plane sees the farmhouse and dreams of home.', 64995, 0), (412407, 'Life has no smooth road for any of us  and in the bracing atmosphere of a high aim the very roughness stimulates the climber to steadier steps till the legend  "over steep ways to the stars " fulfills itself.', 62207, 0), (412408, 'The only normal people are the ones you don''t know very well.', 64996, 0), (412409, 'Before we set our hearts too much upon anything  let us examine how happy they are who already possess it.', 154, 0), (412410, 'What makes us discontented with our condition is the absurdly exaggerated idea we have of the happiness of others.', 33, 0), (412411, 'Nobody''s problem is ideal. Nobody has things just as he would like them.', 62225, 0), (412412, 'Everybody in the world ought to be sorry for everybody else. We all have our little private hell.', 64997, 0), (412413, 'We are convinced that happiness is never to be found  and each believes it possessed by others  to keep alive the hope of obtaining it for himself.', 2087, 0), (412414, 'Men would be angels  angels would be gods.', 3348, 0), (412415, 'None think the great unhappy but the great.', 4028, 0), (412416, 'If every man''s internal care Were written on his brow  How many would our pity share Who raise our envy now?', 62993, 0), (412417, 'Misfortunes come to all men.', 7652, 0), (412418, 'You have no idea how big the other fellow''s troubles are.', 14130, 0), (412419, 'I have been very happy  very rich  very beautiful  much adulated  very famous and very unhappy.', 15813, 0), (412420, 'I feel successful when the writing goes well. This lasts five minutes. Once  when I was on the bestseller list  I also felt successful. That lasted three minutes.', 63279, 0), (412421, 'Great and small suffer the same mishaps.', 144, 0), (412422, 'I thought I had reached a point in life where everything would be smooth. But it is not. It just gets more jagged and pitted and filled with turns that take you into the dark recesses of your mind. It never seems to get easy.', 35699, 0), (412423, 'If I were given a change of life  I''d like to see how it would be to live as a mere six-footer.', 59443, 0), (412424, 'I just want to be an ordinary girl.', 64998, 0), (412425, 'Money is another pressure. I''m not complaining  I''m just saying that there''s a certain luxury in having no money. I spent ten years in New York not having it  not worrying about it. Suddenly you have it  then you worry  where is it going? Am I doing the right thing with it?', 64999, 0), (412426, 'On the outside one is a star. But in reality  one is completely alone  doubting everything. To experience this loneliness of soul is the hardest thing in the world.', 15813, 0), (412427, 'There is no man in this world without some manner of tribulation or anguish  though he be king or pope.', 946, 0), (412428, 'The only incurable troubles of the rich are the troubles that money can''t cure.', 2247, 0), (412429, 'There is no man in any rank who is always at liber